	(85,258,'Texas A&M team wins regional Imperial Barrel Award',X'74657861732D612D6D2D7465616D2D77696E732D726567696F6E616C2D696D70657269616C2D62617272656C2D6177617264','<p><img src=\"images/news/barrel_s.jpg\" alt=\"barrel s\" width=\"245\" height=\"100\" /></p>\r\n<p>Geosciences students qualify for global competition.</p>\r\n','\r\n<h1>Texas A&amp;M team wins regional Imperial Barrel Award</h1>\r\n<p>A team from Texas A&amp;M won first place in the Imperial Barrel Award (IBA) regional contest and have qualified for global competition. The team comprises four graduate students from the Department of Geology and Geophysics. Texas A&amp;M competed against eight other schools in the Gulf Coast region for the honor.</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"wf_caption\" style=\"margin: 10px; float: right; display: inline-block;\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid #000000; margin: auto;\" src=\"images/news/barrel.jpg\" alt=\"barrel\" width=\"526\" height=\"271\" /><span style=\"clear: both; padding: 3px; width: 520px; display: block;\">The 2013 Imperial Barrel Team are, from left, Ilaan Shtaygrud, Robert Schelstrate, David Tilghman, Mitch Blakeley, and Yuefeng Sun, team faculty adviser.</span></span>Sponsored by the American Association of Petroleum Geologists (AAPG), the program is an annual competition for geoscience students around the world. Teams from six U.S. and six international regions, a total of 35 countries, compete for the award. The Texas A&amp;M team will represent the Gulf Coast region in the international competition at the annual AAPG convention held this year May 19-22 in Pittsburgh, Penn.</p>\r\n<p>According to the <a href=\"http://www.aapg.org/iba/\"> IBA program</a> student teams prepare for the contest by studying a dataset of geology, geophysics, land, production infrastructure, and other relevant materials to solve a problem they would face in the energy industry. Each team delivers their results to a panel of industry experts. The judges select the winning team on the basis of the technical quality, clarity and originality of presentation. The winning team receives $20,000 in scholarship funds for its university.</p>\r\n<p>\"Winning the IBA is no small feat,\" said Rick Giardino, head of the Department of Geology and Geophysics. \"The formula for winning requires four dedicated students who are willing to put in hours and hours of every spare minute they have to master the skills and teamwork to operate as a unified team,\" he said.</p>\r\n<p>The Texas A&amp;M team also won in 2009. Geophysics professor Dr. Yuefeng Sun is this year\'s team adviser and coach. Sun is the Mollie B. and Richard A. Williford Professor and head of the department\'s Reservoir Geophysics Program. Team members are Ilaan Shtaygrud, Robert Schelstrate, David Tilghman, and Mitch Blakeley.</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"wf_caption\" style=\"margin: 10px; float: right; display: inline-block;\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid #000000; margin: auto;\" src=\"images/faculty/sun.jpg\" alt=\"sun\" width=\"170\" height=\"220\" /><span style=\"clear: both; padding: 3px; width: 164px; display: block;\">Yuefeng Sun Mollie B. and Richard A. Williford Professor 979.845.6162 sun@geos.tamu.edu</span></span>\"The competition also requires a dedicated coaching team of a faculty member and industry partners, who provide the direction and guidance to mold the students into a polished team,\" Giardino said. He said the competition is not about winning. \"The important lesson is the educational opportunity these students have to use their education, intellect and skills operating in a team problem-solving environment.\" Students winning Imperial Barrel Award competitions are considered highly employable in the energy industry when they graduate.</p>\r\n<table border=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 40px;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"3\">\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><em>April 19, 2013</em></span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Contact<br /></strong><a href=\"mailto:kriedel@tamu.edu\">Karen Riedel</a><br />Communications Manager, College of Geosciences<br />Tel.: 979-845-0910</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 40px;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\"><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/tamu.geosciences.studentlife?ref=ts&amp;fref=ts\"><img src=\"images/facebook_logo.jpg\" alt=\"facebook logo\" width=\"66\" height=\"25\" /></a><br /><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/tamu.geosciences.studentlife?ref=ts&amp;fref=ts\">Join us on FB</a></td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\"><img src=\"images/twitter_logo.jpg\" alt=\"twitter logo\" width=\"68\" height=\"25\" /><br />@GeosciencesTAMU</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>',-2,11,'2013-06-17 14:50:39',8,'','2013-07-12 22:48:22',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-06-17 14:50:39','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',16,7,'','',1,23,'{\"tags\":[3],\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\"}',0,'*',''),
	(86,259,'Geosciences student receives Astronaut Scholarship',X'67656F736369656E6365732D73747564656E742D72656365697665732D617374726F6E6175742D7363686F6C617273686970','<p><img style=\"border: 1px solid #000000; margin: 10px;\" src=\"images/news/amaya_s.jpg\" alt=\"amaya\" width=\"245\" height=\"100\" /></p>\r\n<p>Dillon Amaya, Atmospheric Sciences student, sailed on the NOAA research vessel <em>Ronald H. Brown</em> in spring 2013.</p>\r\n','\r\n<h1>Geosciences student receives Astronaut Scholarship</h1>\r\n<p>A Texas A&amp;M student is one of 28 students nationwide to be awarded a prestigious scholarship from the Astronaut Scholarship Foundation. Dillon Amaya, junior Atmospheric Sciences major, received a $10,000 scholarship in recognition of \"his unique aptitude for research and ingenuity in science and technology,\" according to the award letter.</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"wf_caption\" style=\"margin: 10px; float: right; display: inline-block;\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid #000000; margin: auto;\" src=\"images/news/amaya.jpg\" alt=\"amaya\" width=\"300\" height=\"402\" /><span style=\"clear: both; padding: 3px; width: 294px; display: block;\">aDillon Amaya, Atmospheric Sciences student, sailed on the NOAA research vessel <em>Ronald H. Brown</em> in spring 2013.</span></span>Amaya is the 19th Aggie to receive a scholarship since 1990, and he is only the second student from the College of Geosciences.</p>\r\n<p>\"To me, getting this scholarship has served as complete validation of my educational choices and the direction I\'m heading in my career,\" Amaya said. \"I\'m incredibly grateful to my mentors for all of their support, with special thanks to professors Debbie Thomas, Don Conlee, and Sumana Datta.\"</p>\r\n<p>Astronauts from the foundation make personal visits in the fall to each recipient\'s university to present the scholarship check.</p>\r\n<p>Amaya will continue his undergraduate research under the direction of Thomas, a geological oceanographer. Using sediment samples from the Integrated Ocean Drilling Program (IDOP), he will reconstruct the dust accumulation record for the South Pacific during Earth\'s last major greenhouse climate interval to determine regional climate conditions.</p>\r\n<p>\"Dillon embodies everything the Astronaut Scholarship seeks to reward,\" Thomas said. \"He arrived at Texas A&amp;M aware of undergraduate research opportunities and clearly articulated his desire to drive the science, not simply read about it.\"</p>\r\n<p>Amaya will be in Miami this summer under Greg Foltz at the Atlantic Oceanic and Meteorological Laboratory (AOML). He will investigate the effect El Nino Modoki has on the tropical Atlantic Ocean. The internship is supported by the Ernest F. Hollings Scholarship Program through the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA).</p>\r\n<p>The Astronaut Scholarship Foundation started in 1984 with the six surviving Mercury 7 astronauts. The goal is to aid the United States in retaining its world leadership in science and technology by providing scholarships to the best and brightest STEM students. Today, more than 100 astronauts from the space program raise money through public appearances, fundraisers and memorabilia sales. Scholarship recipients are nominated by a faculty member based on initiative, creativity, and excellence in their chosen field.</p>\r\n<p>\"Dillon quickly evolved from science student to scientist, and he now has assumed a leadership role in my research group,\" Dr. Thomas said. \"He has proven a natural instructor, helping to train and mentor the newer students to prepare samples and interpret the data. His ability to translate his knowledge to others is a testament to his deep understanding of the science.\"</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><em>May 9, 2013</em></span></p>\r\n<p>By Eliana Mijangos \'14</p>\r\n<p><strong>Contact<br /></strong><a href=\"mailto:kriedel@tamu.edu\">Karen Riedel</a><br />Communications Manager, College of Geosciences<br />Tel.: 979-845-0910</p>\r\n<table border=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 40px;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/tamu.geosciences.studentlife?ref=ts&amp;fref=ts\"><img src=\"images/facebook_logo.jpg\" alt=\"facebook logo\" width=\"66\" height=\"25\" /></a><br /><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/tamu.geosciences.studentlife?ref=ts&amp;fref=ts\">Join us on FB</a></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 10px;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\" data-conversation=\"none\"><img src=\"images/twitter_logo.jpg\" alt=\"twitter logo\" width=\"68\" height=\"25\" /><br />@GeosciencesTAMU</blockquote>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>',-2,11,'2013-06-17 14:59:19',8,'','2013-07-11 15:17:10',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-06-17 14:59:19','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',12,6,'','',1,8,'{\"tags\":[3],\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\"}',0,'*','