	(98,287,'Drift Cards Dropped In Gulf Can Reveal Ocean Current Data',X'64726966742D63617264732D64726F707065642D696E2D67756C662D63616E2D72657665616C2D6F6365616E2D63757272656E742D64617461','<p><img src=\"images/news/driftcard_s.jpg\" alt=\"driftcard s\" width=\"245\" height=\"100\" /></p>\r\n<p>Adrift with GISR in the Gulf.</p>\r\n','\r\n<h1>Drift Cards Dropped In Gulf Can Reveal Ocean Current Data&nbsp;</h1>\r\n<p>Coming soon to a beach near you: a \"drift card\" washing up on Gulf of Mexico shores that is part of a research project at Texas A&amp;M University to study ocean currents.</p>\r\n<p><img style=\"margin: 10px; border: 1px solid #000000; float: right;\" src=\"images/news/driftcard.jpg\" alt=\"driftcard\" width=\"300\" height=\"177\" />The brightly colored yellow cards have contact information requesting that finders report where they were found as one way of tracking currents in the Gulf, says Piers Chapman, head of oceanography at Texas A&amp;M. The project is conducted with funding from oil giant BP as part of its Gulf of Mexico Research Initiative.</p>\r\n<p>\"It\'s a fun way to track currents and to get people involved,\" explains Chapman, who has done similar drift card projects before.</p>\r\n<p>The Gulf Integrated Research Consortium will release about 5,000 drift cards over the next few months</p>\r\n<p>\"The cards have contact information on them, asking the finder to call a number or email where he or she found the card, and there will be a monthly drawing for gift cards to encourage finders to respond. We released the first batch of 250 cards on April 6-8 and we\'ve already had about 40 responses. In all, we will release about 5,000 in the next few months.\"</p>\r\n<p>The cards will enable oceanographers to improve prediction models and see how gas and oil travel along the currents of the Gulf.</p>\r\n<p>So far, cards have been retrieved from Alabama to Panama City, Fla., Chapman says.</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"wf_caption\" style=\"margin: 10px; float: right; display: inline-block;\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid #000000; margin: auto;\" src=\"images/faculty/chapman.jpg\" alt=\"chapman\" width=\"209\" height=\"320\" /><span style=\"clear: both; padding: 3px; width: 203px; display: block;\"><a href=\"http://ocean.tamu.edu/profile/PChapman\">Piers Chapman </a><br />Department Head and Professor <br />979.845.7211 <br />pchapman@ocean.tamu.edu</span></span>\"The next several batches will be released farther west, so that\'s when they will eventually wash up on Texas beaches,\" he notes of the cards, written in English and Spanish because some of them will likely be found along the Mexican coast.</p>\r\n<p>Chapman said he was involved in a similar project years ago while working in South Africa.</p>\r\n<p>\"We released drift cards like these and we got them returned from people in Brazil, Australia and along the east coast of Africa,\" he recalls.</p>\r\n<p>\"In a project like this, the typical response rate in the open ocean is about 2 percent, but we are hoping to get a higher return rate in the Gulf of Mexico. However many are returned, we shall get some useful information that will improve our knowledge of Gulf currents.\"</p>\r\n<p><em>May 9, 2013</em></p>\r\n<p>Media contact: Keith Randall, News &amp; Information Services, at 979.845.4644 or Piers Chapman at 979.845.7211</p>',-2,11,'2013-07-11 15:05:01',8,'','2013-07-12 22:46:02',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-11 15:05:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',4,4,'','',1,4,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(99,290,'Robert Duce is appointed to advisory group\'s Gulf of Mexico program',X'726F626572742D647563652D69732D6170706F696E7465642D746F2D61647669736F72792D67726F75702D732D67756C662D6F662D6D657869636F2D70726F6772616D','<p><img src=\"images/news/gulf2_s.jpg\" alt=\"gulf2 s\" width=\"245\" height=\"100\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;Distinguished professor emeritus works for Gulf.</p>\r\n','\r\n<h1>Robert Duce is appointed to advisory group\'s Gulf of Mexico program</h1>\r\n<p>WASHINGTON--Dr. Robert Duce, distinguished professor emeritus of the departments of atmospheric sciences and oceanography at Texas A&amp;M University and former dean of the College of Geosciences, was appointed to an advisory group for the National Academy of Sciences\' Gulf of Mexico program. The advisory group, consisting of individuals with experiences ranging from academia to industry as well as deep connections with the Gulf region, will serve for one year. The new program will focus on human health, environmental protection, and oil system safety in the Gulf of Mexico.</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"wf_caption\" style=\"margin: 10px; float: right; display: inline-block;\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid #000000; margin: auto;\" src=\"images/news/gulf2.jpg\" alt=\"gulf2\" width=\"300\" height=\"183\" /><span style=\"clear: both; padding: 3px; width: 294px; display: block;\">The new program will focus on human health, environmental protection, and oil system safety in the Gulf of Mexico.</span></span>During this time, the group will articulate the program\'s mission, goals and objectives. It will also consider potential metrics to measure the program\'s impacts and outline how the program will operate in the first three to five years. Outgoing NAS Vice President Barbara A. Schaal will chair the group of 24 experts from prestigious institutions such as the NAS, the National Academy of Engineering and the Institute of Medicine.</p>\r\n<p>\"The advisory group brings distinction, expertise from diverse disciplines, and a wide range of experience to the task of defining the program,\" said NAS President Ralph J. Cicerone.</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"wf_caption\" style=\"margin: 10px; float: right; display: inline-block;\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid #000000; margin: auto;\" src=\"images/faculty/duce.jpg\" alt=\"duce\" width=\"170\" height=\"220\" /><span style=\"clear: both; padding: 3px; width: 164px; display: block;\"><a href=\"http://ocean.tamu.edu/profile/RDuce\">Robert Duce </a><br />Former Dean <br />Distinguished Professor Emeritus <br />979.845.5756 <br />rduce@ocean.tamu.edu</span></span>Dr. Duce\'s contribution will come from his varied and successful career studying the oceans and atmosphere. He is a fellow of the American Geophysical Union, the American Meteorological Society, the Oceanography Society and the American Association for the Advancement of Science. He also has won the Rosentiel Award in Atmospheric Chemistry, earned the Distinguished Service Award from the Sea Grant Association and become a national associate of the National Academies.</p>\r\n<p>The $500 million, 30-year program was established as part of the settlements of federal criminal complaints against British Petroleum and Transocean Ltd. following the 2010 Deepwater Horizon explosion, which resulted in 11 deaths, 17 injuries, and the largest oil spill in U.S. history.</p>\r\n<p>The program will focus on human health, environmental protection, and oil system safety in the Gulf of Mexico and the United States\' Outer Continental Shelf. It will fund and carry out studies, projects, and activities in research and development, education and training, and environmental monitoring. The program will be run under the auspices of the National Research Council, the principal operating arm of the NAS and NAE. Together with the IOM, these private, nonprofit institutions provide science, technology, and health policy advice under a congressional charter granted to NAS in 1863. Chris Elfring is the director of the Gulf program at the National Research Council.</p>\r\n<p>Advisory group members and their affiliations at the time of appointment are:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Barbara A. Schaal,</strong><em> Chair</em> (NAS) <br />Dean, Faculty of Arts and Sciences, and Mary-Dell Chilton Distinguished Professor <br />Washington University <br />St. Louis, Missouri</p>\r\n<p><strong>Donald F. Boesch</strong> <br />Professor of Marine Science and President <br />University of Maryland Center for Environmental Science <br />Cambridge, Maryland</p>\r\n<p><strong>Robert S. Carney</strong> <br />Professor Louisiana State University <br />Baton Rouge, Lousiana</p>\r\n<p><strong>Stephen R. Carpenter</strong> (NAS) <br />S.A. Forbes Professor of Zoology <br />University of Wisconsin <br />Madison, Wisconsin</p>\r\n<p><strong>Cortis K. Cooper</strong> <br />Chevron Fellow <br />Chevron Corp. <br />San Ramon, California</p>\r\n<p><strong>Courtney Cowart</strong> <br />Associate Dean, School of Theology <br />Sewanee: The University of the South Sewanee, <br />Tennessee</p>\r\n<p><strong>Robert A. Duce</strong> <br />Distinguished Professor Emeritus <br />Texas A&amp;M University <br />College Station, Texas</p>\r\n<p><strong>Deborah L. Estrin</strong> (NAE) <br />Professor of Computer Science <br />Cornell Tech <br />New York City, N.Y.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Christopher B. Field</strong> (NAS) <br />Director, Department of Global Ecology Carnegie Institution for Science <br />Stanford, California</p>\r\n<p><strong>Gerardo Gold-Bouchot</strong> <br />Professor Center for Research and Advanced Studies <br />Mérida, Mexico</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lynn R. Goldman</strong> (IOM) <br />Dean, School of Public Health and Health Services <br />George Washington University <br />Washington, D.C.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Bernard D. Goldstein</strong> (IOM) <br />Professor Emeritus, Department of Environmental and Occupational Health <br />University of Pittsburgh Graduate School of Public Health <br />Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania</p>\r\n<p><strong>Thomas O. Hunter</strong> <br />Sandia National Laboratories (retired) <br />Albuquerque, N.M.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Shirley Ann Jackson</strong> (NAE) <br />President Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute <br />Troy, N.Y.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Ashanti Johnson</strong> <br />Associate Research Professor <br />University of Texas, Arlington, and Executive Director Institute for Broadening Participation Damariscotta, Maine</p>\r\n<p><strong>David M. Karl</strong> (NAS) <br />Professor of Oceanography <br />University of Hawaii <br />Honolulu, Hawaii</p>\r\n<p><strong>Molly McCammon</strong> <br />Executive Director <br />Alaska Ocean Observing System <br />Anchorage, Alaska</p>\r\n<p><strong>Linda A. McCauley</strong> (IOM) <br />Dean, Emory University <br />Atlanta, Georgia</p>\r\n<p><strong>J. Steven Picou</strong> <br />Professor of Sociology <br />University of South Alabama <br />Mobile, Alabama</p>\r\n<p><strong>Eduardo Salas</strong> <br />Professor of Psychology <br />University of Central Florida <br />Orlando, Florida</p>\r\n<p><strong>Kerry Michael St. Pé</strong> <br />Executive Director Barataria-Terrebonne National Estuary Program <br />Thibodaux, Louisiana Arnold F. Stancell (NAE) Mobil Oil (retired) Greenwich, Connecticut</p>\r\n<p><strong>LaDon Swann</strong> <br />Director of Marine Programs <br />Auburn University <br />Ocean Springs, Mississippi</p>\r\n<p><strong>James W. Ziglar</strong> <br />Senior Counsel Van Ness Feldman <br />Washington, D.C.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Mark D. Zoback</strong> (NAE) <br />Benjamin M. Page Professor, Department of Geophysics <br />Stanford University <br />Palo Alto, California</p>\r\n<p>For more information, and to register to receive updates on the work of the program, including upcoming meetings, please visit www.nas.edu/gulfprogram. June 7, 2013</p>',-2,11,'2013-07-11 15:27:02',8,'','2013-07-11 15:48:05',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-11 15:27:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',4,3,'','',1,20,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(100,291,'Dean\'s Welcome',X'77656C636F6D65','','<hr class=\"system-pagebreak\" title=\"Welcome\" />\r\n<h1><img style=\"margin: 0px 0px 20px 10px; border: 1px solid #000000; float: right;\" src=\"images/dean/miller.jpg\" alt=\"miller\" width=\"195\" height=\"326\" />Howdy!</h1>\r\n<p>As Dean of the College of Geosciences at Texas A&amp;M University, it is my pleasure to welcome you to our college. The College of Geosciences educates students in the Atmospheric Sciences and Meteorology, Geography, Geology and Geophysics, Oceanography, Environmental Programs and Water Management and Hydrologic Science. We provide our students the academic foundation and resources needed to become the scientists, educators, technicians, policymakers, and industry leaders who will shape the future of our planet.</p>\r\n<p>The vision for our college is to lead in establishing the geosciences as the most important and impactful scientific discipline of the 21st century. We are doing that by advancing new understandings of Earth\'s systems and applying them to the needs of society. We are also dedicated to preparing the next generation of geoscientists.</p>\r\n<p>Discovery truly begins here, and we invite you to be a part of this critically important endeavor. We, the faculty, students and staff and of the Geosciences Aggie family, encourage you to visit us in person, through our website or both. As you explore the College of Geosciences\' academic departments, programs and research centers, let us know if you have any questions or need further information.</p>\r\n<p>Contact my office at 979.845.3651 or email dean@geosciences.tamu.edu. Thank you and gig \'em!</p>\r\n<p>Kate C. Miller <br />Dean</p>\r\n<hr class=\"system-pagebreak\" title=\"About Dean Miller\" />\r\n<h1>About Dean Miller</h1>\r\n<p>Dean Kate C. Miller came to Texas A&amp;M in the fall of 2009 as dean of the College of Geosciences and professor of geology and geophysics. She is the college\'s 11th dean.</p>\r\n<p>Previous to this appointment, Dr. Miller held teaching and several administrative positions at the University of Texas at El Paso (UTEP), including associate dean in the College of Science and chair of the Department of Geological Sciences. She began her career in the oil patch as a development geologist and exploration geophysicist for Amoco Production (now BP) in New Orleans.</p>\r\n<p>Dr. Miller\'s primary research interests focus on applying geophysical techniques to investigations of the origin and evolution of the continental lithosphere and to improving understanding of earthquakes and other environmental hazards.</p>\r\n<p>Her fieldwork has ranged from the West Coast of North America, the Rocky Mountains and the Great Plains to eastern and central Europe. She continues to be actively involved in the <a href=\"http://www.bighorns.org/\">Bighorn Project,</a> sponsored by the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.earthscope.org/\">NSF EarthScope Program</a> and AFRL. The project involves faculty and students from five universities who are investigating the formation of the Rockies.</p>\r\n<p>While at UTEP, Dr. Miller was active in a broad range of educational and retention programs, initiatives that she brought to Texas A&amp;M. She works statewide with public school and higher education professionals to provide better access to the STEM disciplines. Along with the dean of the Jackson School at the University of Texas, she is a founding partner of&nbsp;<a href=\"http://digtexas.org/\">DIG Texas,</a> an organization whose mission is to recruit students from an increasingly diverse Texas population into college-level geosciences. Since her arrival, the College of Geosciences has consistently increased each year in student enrollment and in minority representation.</p>\r\n<p>Dr. Miller manages a comprehensive geosciences program comprising departments of atmospheric sciences, geography, geology and geophysics, and oceanography and interdisciplinary programs in water management and in environmental geoscience. In addition, she has responsibility for Texas Sea Grant, which provides research and service to the Texas Gulf Coast, the Integrated Ocean Drilling program—the National Science Foundation\'s largest earth-sciences program—and the Geochemical and Environmental Research Group, which conducts environmental research worldwide. Although Geosciences is the smallest of the 10 colleges at Texas A&amp;M, its research activities account for 19 percent of the university\'s federal funds.</p>\r\n<p>Dr. Miller received her bachelor\'s degree from Princeton University in 1982, and her master\'s and doctoral degrees in geophysics from Stanford University in 1988 and 1991. She received the UT System Chancellor\'s Council Award for Teaching Excellence while at UTEP. She is also a fellow of the Geological Society of America.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"files/KateMillerCV.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Kate C. Miller CV</a><br /><a href=\"http://geoweb.tamu.edu/profile/KMiller\">Faculty Profile</a></p>\r\n<hr class=\"system-pagebreak\" title=\"Speeches\" />\r\n<h1>Speeches</h1>\r\n<p><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=125&amp;Itemid=210\">March 3, 2012: Scholarship Banquet</a><br /><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=124&amp;Itemid=211\">November 3, 2012: Broadcast Meteorology Workshop</a><br /><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=123&amp;Itemid=212\">June 1, 2012: GeoX</a><br /><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=122&amp;Itemid=213\">May 2012: Graduate Reception</a><br /><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=120&amp;Itemid=214\">April 12, 2012: Berg-Hughes Conference</a><br /><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=119&amp;Itemid=215\">October 17, 2011: Sea Grant</a><br /><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=118&amp;Itemid=216\">October 14, 2011: GEODAC Remarks</a><br /><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=117&amp;Itemid=217\">September 29, 2011: New Administrators Reception</a><br /><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=117&amp;Itemid=217\">August 2011: Convocation</a><br /><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=115&amp;Itemid=219\">May 14, 2010: Graduation Reception</a><br /><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=121&amp;Itemid=220\">May 12, 2010: Berg-Hughes Center Inaugural Conference</a><br /><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=126&amp;Itemid=221\">April 22, 2010: CACE Conference</a><br /><a href=\"index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=127&amp;Itemid=222\">February 19, 2010: Science is a Blast</a></p>\r\n<hr class=\"system-pagebreak\" title=\"Media\" />\r\n<h1>Media</h1>\r\n<p>To download high-resolution PDF images, click on images.</p>\r\n<div class=\"grid_six\"><a href=\"images/dean/photoset/image1.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"margin: 0px 10px 10px; float: left;\" src=\"images/dean/photoset/image1s.jpg\" alt=\"Dean Miller\" width=\"100\" height=\"140\" /></a>Also available as <a href=\"images/dean/photoset/image1.jpg\" target=\"_blank\">low-res jpg</a></div>\r\n<div class=\"grid_six jblast\"><a href=\"images/dean/photoset/image2.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"margin: 0px 10px 10px; float: left;\" src=\"images/dean/photoset/image2s.jpg\" alt=\"Dean Miller\" width=\"100\" height=\"140\" /></a>Also available as <a href=\"images/dean/photoset/image2.jpg\" target=\"_blank\">low-res jpg</a></div>',-2,23,'2013-07-11 18:08:08',8,'','2013-07-12 16:29:53',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-11 18:08:08','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\