	(115,310,'May 14, 2010: Graduation Reception',X'6D61792D31342D323031302D67726164756174696F6E2D726563657074696F6E','<h1>May 14, 2010: Graduation Reception</h1>\r\n<h2>Graduate Reception, Class of 2010</h2>\r\n<p>May 14, 2010</p>\r\n<p><strong>INTRODUCTION</strong></p>\r\n<p>Howdy, Welcome to the Colleges of Geosciences Graduation Reception honoring the Class of 2010.<br />It is a pleasure to be here this afternoon to join our graduates in celebrating this important landmark in life with students parents, friends and relatives. Tomorrow, you will participate in the larger ceremony at Reed Arena. You\'ve probably noticed that we commonly use two different terms for that ceremony \"graduation\" and \"commencement\". And with good reason. Both refer to \"receiving or conferring of an academic degree or diploma\".</p>\r\n<p>But \"graduation\" also refer to the action of dividing a scale into proportionate divisions or steps.\" If you think about it, those proportionate divisions are really a lot like each of the classes that you took in order to accumulate the credits required to achieve your degree. When you first arrived at Texas A&amp;M, the idea of taking so many steps must have seemed daunting. The idea of graduation was a very distance, nebulous goal. And yet, here you are today, having persistently taken one step at time to eventually attain your goal. There is a take away message about success in life in this process. Think big, have vision, but never allow the size of your vision to overwhelm you – you will be able to get there, one step at a time.</p>\r\n<p>Which brings to me the other term for graduation, \"commencement\". \"Commencement\", also means \"a beginning\" or a \"start\". With your new degree in hand, bachelors, masters, or Ph.D., you must now be ready to start down a new road in your life. The choices you make will further define who you are as a person. Beginnings represent incredible opportunity but can also be daunting. Not to worry, your education at Texas A&amp;M has given you many skills to assure your success. You have certainly acquired the important content knowledge and technical skills that will assure your success as professionals. You have expertise with tools ranging from pick axes and rock hammers to radar and sonar. You use seismographs, and chromatographs, and magnetometers, bucket thermometers and fathometers. More importantly, in your years here, you have, perhaps unknowingly, also grown your abilities to communicate well, to respect and interact with others who come from different backgrounds than your own, and to think critically and creatively, not only about geoscience, but about life. With all these skills you can \"begin\" the next phase with confidence.</p>\r\n<p>Along the way, I certainly hope that you have found how much fun the Geosciences are. Many of you have experienced adventures at field camp, voyages on research ships and trips to Brazilian rain forests, Southwestern deserts, the Antarctic and the Caribbean, and places in between. Many of you have also experienced, through your research, the excitement of creating new knowledge – information or an idea that no one has heard of before. Life should be fun and exciting.</p>\r\n<p>Today you graduate with degrees in Geosciences at a time when our field has never been more important to society. Energy, water, climate, and the environment are on everyone\'s minds. The questions are many. How will we live sustainably and maintain a high standard of living? How can we ensure our resilience for bouncing back from disaster – natural or man made? How will we adapt to climate change? It is you graduates that we will be relying on to answer these questions.</p>\r\n<p>The ongoing political and technical response to the oil spill in the Gulf of Mexico is an outstanding example of how geoscientists and society are coming together to grapple with these kinds of questions. Oil and gas will undoubtedly remain central to our energy needs for many years to come. Broadly, society understands that we must continue to explore for and develop hydrocarbon resources. Here at Texas A&amp;M, we will continue to train graduates for that industry to assure the nation\'s energy supply.</p>\r\n<p>On the other hand, the spill, is an example of the price we and our environment pay for our energy quest. Here at Texas A&amp;M we are also training the graduates who have the knowledge to help industry and government respond to and mitigate the effects of such a spill. For example, the Texas A&amp;M buoy network, which among other things, measures currents in the Gulf of Mexico, is helping to predict the path of the spill and where it will hit the coast. By being able to predict the path of the spill, we can help government respond more effectively and reduce the environmental effects of the spill.</p>\r\n<p>Over the last couple of weeks, Dr. Chapman, Head of Oceanography, has been interviewed regularly by the press about this, most recently he was interviewed on live on Fox News, yesterday afternoon. Of course, many future studies will occur and may new lessons will learned from this event, so that we will be sure to prepare better in the future. I know that, we the faculty at Texas A&amp;M as well as your family and friends are reassured that we will be able to rely on outstanding graduates like you to be lead these kinds of important environmental solutions in the future.<br />And now it is time to begin the real celebration. Before I ask the Class of 2010 to stand and be recognized, I first want to acknowledge some other very important people.</p>\r\n<p>Let me begin by asking those faculty members who are present to please stand and be recognized. It is they that have worked tirelessly to prepare you for the future by challenging you to perform at your best, and still be there to support you when you thought the challenge was insurmountable. I\'m sure you appreciate their efforts even more than I do.<br />Supporting the faculty and the college, are many staff members, including advisors who have helped you navigate the system here at Texas A&amp;M. Would those staff members who are present, please stand and accept our thanks for your outstanding work.</p>\r\n<p>Wherever there are successful graduates, there are parents, family, and close friends who have faithfully sacrificed and supported them as they pursued their goal. Would all parents, family, and friends of graduates who are here please stand and be recognized. They couldn\'t have done it without you. We could not have done it without you. Thank you.<br />Now, I will ask the graduates, grouped by degree and department, to stand and accept our congratulations. You may be seated after you are recognized by the audience.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Graduates receiving a bachelor of science in Meteorology, please stand.</li>\r\n<li>Graduates receiving a bachelor of science in environmental geosciences and environmental studies, please stand.</li>\r\n<li>Graduates receiving a bachelor of science in Geography. . . . in Spatial Science . . . and in University Studies, please stand.</li>\r\n<li>Graduates receiving a bachelor degrees in Geology and Geophysics, please stand.</li>\r\n<li>Those receiving a master of science degree in Atmospheric Science, Geography, Geology and Oceanography, please stand.</li>\r\n<li>And, now for our highest degree. Those receiving a doctorate in Atmospheric Sciences, Oceanography, Geography and Hydrologic Sciences, please stand.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>I will now turn the program over to Dr. Sarah Bednarz, Associate Dean, in the College of Geosciences, to lead our recognition of academically outstanding graduates.</p>\r\n<p><strong>CONCLUSION</strong></p>\r\n<p>We know great things will come from all the graduates. Please keep in touch. Send email and check out the web site.</p>\r\n<p>We like to brag about the success of our former students.</p>\r\n<p>Again, congratulations class of 2010! We will see you tomorrow at 9 am at Reed Arena.</p>','',-2,50,'2013-07-12 15:39:32',8,'','2013-07-12 16:02:53',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 15:39:32','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',1,10,'','',1,1,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(116,311,'August 2011: Convocation',X'6175677573742D323031312D636F6E766F636174696F6E','<h1>August 2011: Convocation</h1>\r\n<h2>Geosciences Class of 2015 Welcome</h2>\r\n<p>August 2011</p>\r\n<p>Howdy.<br />I am Kate Miller, dean of Geosciences. On behalf of the faculty, staff, and students, I welcome you, the members of the class of 2015, your family and your friends to campus as we begin a new school year.</p>\r\n<p>We are excited to have you here. This is my third year to stand before the incoming class, and I am proud to say that as each year progresses, our College becomes stronger and more prominent on the local, state and national levels. Its programs, professors and performance improve each year, which means that your future career in geosciences is brighter than ever.<br />You basically need three things to succeed in our college. You need the faculty to teach you, the programs to support you, and your desire to work with us to help you succeed.</p>\r\n<p>Let me tell you a little about your faculty. Ask yourselves. What has been in the headlines lately, other than the buzz of ceaseless political bickering? Hurricanes. Drought. Earthquakes. Earlier this year Japan suffered an earthquake and a tsunami. And the Gulf oil spill of 16 months go is still an ongoing challenge. Add into this mix gasoline prices, environmental quality, population growth, and the continual search for alternative energy, for better water management, for better stewardship of our natural and human resources. Your faculty researches, writes about and teaches all these topics and more every single day.</p>\r\n<p>Our faculty includes the Texas state climatologist, whose knowledge, advice and opinions on the drought and on climate change are sought daily by the media, decision makers and fellow researchers.</p>\r\n<p>One of our department heads devised a method to track how fast and in what direction the wind would from the damaged nuclear reactors in Japan to the United States.</p>\r\n<p>Our professors, including students, were the first to sample at the wellhead of the DeepWater Horizon oil spill, the first to identify and map the dead zone in the Gulf of Mexico and, tomorrow, we have the first group of students leaving with two professors to study geology and oceanography in Italy. We took Aggies and other university students from around the country to a Costa Rican cloud forest this summer. This summer students in Belize mapped coral reefs, and they sailed on board ships from the Gulf Coast to the Antarctica. Right now, students are at the North Pole sampling methane, a far different environment from the Gulf of Mexico.</p>\r\n<p>So, when you hear that professors at a Tier One research university do not come out of their labs, are not interested in teaching, don\'t care about anything but research, they are not talking about those in Geosciences.</p>\r\n<p>I do not make rash promises, but I do promise you this: you will have classes with internationally recognized professors at the top of their fields, people who are eager to introduce you to the subjects they have dedicated their lives to.</p>\r\n<p>The second thing you need to know is that we have the programs, the staff, and the commitment to help you succeed. Not a day goes by that we do not discuss new and better ways to serve you. Over the last three years, we have initiated first-year workshops to help you study better, organize your time, and manage your finances. We have peer mentoring, student ambassadors and a network of staff, faculty and student advisors who are on hand to help you succeed. We have implemented iGeo. Do we have any iGeo alumni here? Please stand up (applause). The iGeo program brings high school juniors and seniors to campus one weekend in the fall to take classes, meet professors and experience campus living capped by a tailgate party and tickets to an Aggie football game. This past year, we started GeoX, a weeklong program in the summer for high-school juniors that introduces them to all Geosciences has to offer. And just a month ago, we sent our first class of G-Camp for students off for a 15-day bus tour of Texas, where they not only learned the geology of the state from one end to the other, they also received 4 hours of science credit. Do we have any G-Campers here? Please stand. [Applause].</p>\r\n<p>The third leg of success is you. You are here because of a lot of hard work. Your parents worked hard, from the day you were born, to get you here. Congratulations, parents. You did good.</p>\r\n<p>We worked really hard to get you here, too, through the programs I just mentioned and through outreach, recruitment and personal contact.</p>\r\n<p>And I know you worked hard to get here. You had to take the math and science, the tests and all of the other hurdles I am sure you remember only too well. But you did get here. So, now I must ask you to continue working with us to make sure that these four years are a time of learning, of discovery and of joy. I plan to watch every one of you four years from now walk across that stage and receive your diploma. That\'s my dream. Let\'s make it happen together.</p>','',-2,50,'2013-07-12 15:40:33',8,'','2013-07-12 16:02:53',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 15:40:33','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',2,9,'','',1,0,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(117,312,'September 29, 2011: New Administrators Reception',X'73657074656D6265722D32392D323031312D6E65772D61646D696E6973747261746F72732D726563657074696F6E','<h1>September 29, 2011: New Administrators Reception</h1>\r\n<h2>New administrators reception</h2>\r\n<p>September 29, 2011</p>\r\n<p>Halbouty</p>\r\n<p>Howdy. We are here today to welcome the newest members to our College of Geosciences community. Two new leaders have joined us, and two experienced members—I am not saying old!—have new positions.</p>\r\n<p>First, I am pleased to introduce Eric Riggs who is not only new to the college but also fills a newly created position. Eric is assistant dean for diversity and graduate student recruitment and development. Eric is the person in helping implement Texas A&amp;M\'s diversity plan for faculty, staff and students. We also count on Eric to bring our graduate recruitment efforts on par with our successful undergraduate initiatives.</p>\r\n<p>Eric is a structural geologist, and he has an office in Halbouty as well as the dean\'s office in O&amp;M. I know you will find it a pleasure to get to know and work with Eric as we achieve our goal of becoming a national model for recruiting and retaining the faculty and students who reflect our state and nation.</p>\r\n<p>Our other new administrator is Pam Plotkin, Sea Grant\'s new director. Pam arrived here from upper New York state. . . .In July . . . In the middle of the state\'s worst drought. . . With record-high temperatures. In August, the building that houses Sea Grant was threatened by wildfire. So despite this Texas-sized \"welcome,\" I am l glad to see that Pam is still with us. And, rather than \"Welcome, Pam,\" I want to say, \"welcome back.\" Pam knew what she was getting into when she accepted our offer. Before taking off for cooler climates at Cornell, and other states \"back East,\" she earned her master\'s and doctorate degrees from Geosciences. Pam takes over the helm of a very fine, well-run and committed organization, one that serves Texas up and down the coast every day. Texas Sea Grant celebrates its 40th anniversary this year, and it serves as a model for other Sea Grants across the country. I know we all look forward to continued success and service as Pam initiates the next four decades of the Sea Grant story.</p>\r\n<p>The next two administrators are known to most of us in the college, and I am especially grateful to have their experience, proven administrative ability and an understanding of our college\'s history and vision. Rick Giardino is the new department head for Geology and Geophysics. It would take me most of the afternoon to cite Rick\'s many administrative accomplishments, teaching awards and honors. But I will say that through programs such as G-Camp for Teachers, Rick has earned the respect of public school teachers, counselors and principals throughout the state. I venture to say that is a tougher audience than even the faculty and staff in Geology and Geophysics.</p>\r\n<p>After serving as interim for the past year, Vatche Tcharkerian has graciously accepted the position of department head in Geography. This department is our most diverse in terms of subject matter, variety and faculty research interests, and it requires a leader with a solid foundation in science and in the humanities. No one fills that bill better than Vatche whose wide range of interests and his research in physical geography, technology and the arts gives him the perspective to lead such an interdisciplinary program. I welcome him back on board, and I look forward to his support in increasing Geography\'s already growing national and international reputation.<br />Please join me in giving a big howdy to these folks who have joined us in helping make our college the</p>','',-2,50,'2013-07-12 15:42:21',8,'','2013-07-12 16:02:53',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 15:42:21','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',1,8,'','',1,3,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(118,313,'October 14, 2011: GEODAC Remarks',X'6F63746F6265722D31342D323031312D67656F6461632D72656D61726B73','<h1>October 14, 2011: GEODAC Remarks</h1>\r\n<h2>GEODAC Remarks</h2>\r\n<p>Oct. 14, 2011</p>\r\n<p>Howdy,</p>\r\n<p>Welcome to the annual meeting of the Geology and Geophysics Department\'s Advisory Committee meeting. Later this morning, you will hear a review of the Berg-Hughes Center. I am here to say a few words of thanks for your help in making sure this center thrives.</p>\r\n<h3>Where we were</h3>\r\n<p>When I interviewed in 2008, the Berg-Hughes Center was in the earliest stages of development.<br />Parents for this fledgling enterprise were, in addition to the Hughes family and Mrs. Berg, Carlos Dengo, Tom Kelly, Dustin Marshall, Dan Pedrotti, Thomas Ruffer, Winston Sexton, Ken Williams and Clayton Williams.</p>\r\n<h3>Where we are</h3>\r\n<p>In a little more than two years, Berg-Hughes\' students, faculty and research activities are flourishing. With 40-plus students, more than half on fellowships thanks to your generosity, we are leaving the toddler stage and fast approaching our prime.</p>\r\n<p>Andreas Kronenberg and Diane Barron served as midwives, helping to bring the center into the light of day. It is now in the capable hands of Ernie Mancini, a modest man with extraordinary vision.</p>\r\n<h3>Where we want to be</h3>\r\n<p>Texas A&amp;M is less than 90 miles from the heart of the U.S. oil and gas industry—with more than 300 major companies headquartered or with offices in Houston.<br />No other place in the world has such a high concentration of energy sector companies. And no other Tier One university is as close as Texas A&amp;M. Just as Stanford is the nexus of Silicon Valley, Texas A&amp;M, through the Berg-Hughes Center for Sedimentary and Petroleum Center, is fast becoming synonymous with oil and gas.</p>\r\n<p>As universities face the new economic realities, the need for cross-disciplinary cooperation is imperative. Berg-Hughes exemplifies the kind of collaborative effort, both within the College of Geosciences and through its partnership with the College of Engineering. As Berg-Hughes grows up–skipping, I hope, adolescence–I am confident that the future leaders of energy companies around the world will not only wear the Aggie ring but will also have the Berg-Hughes experience as part of their portfolio.</p>\r\n<p>I believe all of you in this room are as proud of this program as I am. If we have come this far in a little more than two years, just imagine where we can go from here. Thank you again for your support.</p>','',-2,50,'2013-07-12 15:43:24',8,'','2013-07-12 16:02:53',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 15:43:24','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',1,7,'','',1,1,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(119,314,'October 17, 2011: Sea Grant',X'6F63746F6265722D31372D323031312D7365612D6772616E74','<h1>October 17, 2011: Sea Grant</h1>\r\n<h2>Sea Grant Anniversary Remarks</h2>\r\n<p>Oct. 17, 2011</p>\r\n<p>Howdy,</p>\r\n<p>It is my honor to welcome you to Texas Sea Grant\'s 40th anniversary celebration. Extension Program (TXSGE) staff are the most visible face of Texas Sea Grant, so it\'s only fitting that we feature the TXSGE staff\'s faces and some of their work in a calendar celebrating the Program\'s 40 years of service to Texans.</p>\r\n<p>I do not have the time today to enumerate all tremendous successes Sea Grant has accomplished these past 4 decades. I will tell you that Texas Sea Grant is essential to Texans who depend on our coastal resources for a living, for recreation and for a legacy to leave to future generations.</p>\r\n<p>Note I said I did not have time to enumerate, but I will give you some numbers.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s start with this:</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">$50 million dollars. The amount of money Sea Grant awarded over the last 40 years competitive research grants to study critical issues like coastal erosion, harmful algal blooms, endangered sea turtles, coastal hazards and aquaculture.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">$1 to $6 ratio. For every dollar that Sea Grant receives from the Texas Legislature, it brings in six additional dollars from outside funding.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">30 years: The length of time Gary Graham, marine fisheries specialist has served Texans. His expertise in developing or improving tools such as shrimp trawls, turtle excluder and bycatch reduction devices have helped countless in the fishing industry.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">Thousands: The immeasurable number of high school students across the country who have competed at the state and national levels in programs such as the National Ocean Sciences Bowl, and the regional competitions, the Dolphin and Loggerhead Challenges.<br />And also in the hundreds if not more: Texas students have been enchanted by Sea Grant\'s Floating Classroom on board Karma, home ported in Corpus Christi.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">800: The number of cold-stunned sea turtles rescued by 80 volunteers in the 2010 cold snap</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">604 pounds or about 820 miles: Weight and length of monofilament fiber removed as a result of the recovery and recycling program created by Sea Grant.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">400,000+ volunteers: Sea Grant conceived what grew into the Adopt a Beach program; these volunteers have picked up more than 8,100 tons of trash since its inception in 1986.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">2.4 million: The gallons of fuel saved in just one year by Texas shrimpers who used Sea Grants\' fuel-efficient trawling gear.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">200: estimated number of shrimping-industry jobs saved because of better fuel efficiencies.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">56,300: The number of hours spent in just one year on projects such as restoring more than 3,400 acres of dune and wetland habitats and developing 20.2 miles of nature trails.</p>\r\n<p>Think about these numbers the next time you eat a shrimp cocktail in Corpus Christi, or build sand castles with your kids in Port Aransas or listen to the foghorns in Galveston. Texas Sea Grant and Extension is truly one of our state\'s treasures. I join with all of you in wishing it many more decades of successful service to Texas.</p>','',-2,50,'2013-07-12 15:44:18',8,'','2013-07-12 16:02:53',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 15:44:18','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',1,6,'','',1,1,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(120,315,'April 12, 2012: Berg-Hughes Conference',X'617072696C2D31322D323031322D626572672D6875676865732D636F6E666572656E6365','<h1>April 12, 2012: Berg-Hughes Conference</h1>\r\n<p>April 12, 2012</p>\r\n<p>Howdy!</p>\r\n<p>Welcome to the third annual Berg-Hughes Conference. Thank you for coming to support our students, faculty and researchers.</p>\r\n<p>This year we are delighted—and proud—to present a program that focuses on student research. The people who support and those who lead the Berg-Hughes Center envisioned such a day, where young people not yet in the workforce, would research and present solutions to real-world problems. We in the College of Geosciences are dedicated to student research experiences in all of the geosciences departments. As educators, we have seen firsthand that individual research gives students critical skills in analytical thinking, creative problem-solving and organized presentation of material. This is the cusp where students first experience the culture of research and the life of a scientist. It is this voyage to discovery, the \"aha\" moment that compels us all to continue our restless quest for knowledge.</p>\r\n<p>For the scientist, the \"aha\" moments are often too often few and far between. But they will occur. It occurs when all your classes in physics and math, in geology and mineralogy, your observations, and perhaps most important, your intuition, come together. You will see a connection no one else has ever made, and then you will know why you are on this journey.</p>\r\n<p>I am reminded of one of my personal role models, Harry Hammond Hess. His example inspires me on several levels—and not just for his being a graduate from and the longtime head of the geology department at Princeton, my alma mater. Alas, he died before I arrived, but his imprint remains.</p>\r\n<p>But first, take a step back and imagine this. Less than 70 years ago, the world\'s oceans and what lay beneath them were as much a mystery to us as the moon. We did not know—although we suspected--that the continents somehow fit together, but how and why? Less than 60 years ago, we did not know that the history of Earth\'s magnetic field reversals were banded in ocean sediment, as graphically readable as tree rings. We did not know that the seafloor formed and spread at mid-ocean ridges only to be eventually consumed into the \"jaw crusher\"—as Hess called it—of the deep trenches.</p>\r\n<p>By mid-20th century, the geological sciences were an afterthought. Science was dominated by the physicists, evolutionary biologists, geneticists and even Freudian psychoanalysts. But then emerged a generation of scientists who redefined earth\'s processes. Hess\'s contemporaries are Morley, Vine and Matthews, Bruce Heezen, Marie Tharpe, Maurice \"Doc\" Ewing, Robert Dietz, John Tuzo Wilson, Xavier Le Pichon and many more. They teased out the details but Hess provided the unifying theory of plate tectonics.</p>\r\n<p>It is said that he possessed two critical skills: careful attention to detail and the ability—and confidence—to form sweeping hypotheses. As a Navy commander during World War II, he relentlessly scanned the seafloor with sounding gear as his ship cruised from one battle to the next, revealing a morphology of the seafloor very different from what had been previously imagined.</p>\r\n<p>After the war, he completed his education and began his life as a faculty member. In 1960, he produced a \"modest\" report for the Office of Naval Research that triggered a revolution in Earth sciences. He turned the report into the book The History of Ocean Basins. Allow me to read the first sentence: \"The birth of the oceans is a matter of conjecture, the subsequent history is obscure, and the present structure is just beginning to be understood.\" He wrote that his work was merely an \"essay in geopoetry.\" He then put forth the boldest scientific claim in the history of geosciences. His audacious intuition was quickly corroborated: the age of the ocean increases the further away it is from ocean ridges; oceanic crust sinks into the jaw-crusher trenches; and the age of the ocean is a mere few hundred million years old, significantly younger than the continents.</p>\r\n<p>From advising on the Mohole and the scientific program for DSDP\'s<em> Glomar Challenger</em> to serving on President Kennedy\'s Space Science Board, Hess was part the largest revolution in earth science. In his obituary, a colleague wrote that Hess had five lives: (1) family man, (2) Princeton graduate and faculty member, (3) a Navy officer, (4) a mineralogist, geologist, geological geophysicist and oceanographer, and (5) an administrator, fundraiser and organizer.</p>\r\n<p>If he were here today, I imagine that Harry Hess would whole-heartedly endorse your support of student research. We do have among us today a man who reflects the qualities and intensity of Harry Hess, a man also known for his many different lives and, like Hess, a man know for a scientific life well-lived. Bill Bryant shares with Hess a relentless thirst for scientific truth. Like him Bill\'s research crosses disciplines and spans the world. Technically he is a geological oceanographer, but again, that is like saying Hess is mineralogist. For nearly 50 years, Bill Bryant has been engaged in research and the practical applications of geology, oceanography, geophysics, geotechnology, and marine archeology.</p>\r\n<p>Bill\'s quest has led him as far as both poles and as close as the Gulf of Mexico—its basins and canyons, bumps and curves, he probably knows as well as any man on Earth. He later turned this knowledge to nautical archeology, leading an expedition off the coast of Louisiana to one of the deepest shipwreck sites ever explored.</p>\r\n<p>Others today will talk about Bill Bryant\'s remarkable career. But, for me, one example sums up who he is. Bill Bryant is the first person at Texas A&amp;M to receive all three of the Association of Former Students\' highest university-level awards—for research in 1982, for teaching in 2001 and for mentoring in 2007. To call someone a Renaissance person probably became a cliché a couple of centuries ago, but I can think of no better expression to describe someone as accomplished in so many scientific disciplines, and yet who is still driven to instill the quest for scientific truth in future generations. We will hear more today about Bill\'s many accomplishments. But for now, I look forward to learning along with you from our newest generation of scientists.</p>\r\n<p>Thanks to all of you who have supported the Berg-Hughes Center and its mission to create this new generation of scientist-explorers. Thank you, students, for your hard work, and I am sure some sleepless nights as you prepared your presentations. And thank you Ernie Mancini for being the unifying theorist behind the Berg-Hughes Center. Others may have provided the details, but your leadership has pulled it together.</p>','',-2,50,'2013-07-12 15:46:04',8,'','2013-07-12 16:02:53',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 15:46:04','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',1,5,'','',1,1,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(121,316,'May 12, 2010: Berg-Hughes Center Inaugural Conference',X'6D61792D31322D323031302D626572672D6875676865732D63656E7465722D696E6175677572616C2D636F6E666572656E6365','<h1>May 12, 2010: Berg-Hughes Center Inaugural Conference</h1>\r\n<p>Howdy! And welcome to the Berg-Hughes inaugural workshop and research conference. It has been an amazing year—even less than a year—the center just opened in July 2009 . . . and in this time we hired a director, secured the funding and the facilities, and gathered nearly 30 faculty members to teach the more than 60 courses now available. We debuted the center at AAPG a month ago in April, and now we are holding our first research conference. This just shows what Aggies can do when given a project and the premise that what we do today will benefit our students . . . and the state . . . now and in the future.</p>\r\n<p>Our world is more complex, more so even than a year ago. Changes in technology and an increasing understanding of earth\'s processes combined with economic, political and environmental challenges on a global scale make us reassess every day how we go about doing things. I believe that the Berg-Hughes Center provides ballast in the storm by combining the strengths of two colleges and the feedback and advice from industry.</p>\r\n<p>Today at this conference you will hear precisely the issues that universities and industry are discussing. You will hear not only about petroleum and sedimentary problems and solutions, but you will also learn how each of the departments involved—petroleum engineering, oceanography, and geology and geophysics—fit together, a unified whole whose sum is better than its parts. You will hear from students, perhaps some who are presenting research results for the first time. And you will also learn from some of the university\'s most distinguished faculty members. Industry leaders are here as well.</p>\r\n<p>Sometimes, we do live in an ivory tower and, in our case, literally if you have seen the O&amp;M Building. So, to have the opportunity to learn from professionals in the field who have taken time from their companies to make sure that we understand what the priorities are and how we can help provide the solutions means a lot to all of us.</p>\r\n<p>I am excited about this center and about its potential. I am proud the College is part of what is already fertile ground for research and technology transfer, a process that contributes to the economy and the energy needs of this state and beyond.</p>\r\n<p>I truly believe that in five, ten years, our students will lead the field, that they alone will have the background to understand both geoscientific and engineering principles, concepts and methods. They will have a solid foundation in the fundamentals and a research experience unmatched by any university. This program will give them the leadership skills, technical knowledge and intellectual capacity to attack problems and find solutions. These will be the next \"best in the field,\" and they will be at the top because of the Berg-Hughes Center and the people in this room.</p>\r\n<p>Before I close, I want to thank the person who is the driving force behind this center . . . and this conference, Ernie Mancini. You are—we all are—here today because of Ernie\'s devotion, dedication and vision. I also thank Steve Holditch, from Petroleum Engineering, whose enthusiasm took Ernie\'s vision to the next level. The other members of this founding team of Berg-Hughers are Bill Bryant and Andreas Kronenberg. Now, Bill is such a giant in the field of oceanography that he occupies his own named chair. The Bill Bryant Chair for Teaching, Research and Mentoring recognizes the trifecta of awards he has received from the Association of Former Students. As chair of the geology and geophysics department, Andreas has enough to do without taking on another project. However, Andreas helped the center see the light of day in record time, bringing through proposal through the bureaucratic process with the tenacity of a bulldog and the skill of an Italian diplomat. I would like to thank all four of you gentlemen for your significant contributions.</p>\r\n<p>So, enjoy the day. Along with you I look forward to hearing the presentations, and I encourage you to participate with questions and comments at the end of the session, so we can all learn from each other.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','',-2,50,'2013-07-12 15:47:17',8,'','2013-07-12 16:02:53',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 15:47:17','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',1,11,'','',1,1,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(122,317,'May 2012: Graduate Reception',X'6D61792D323031322D67726164756174652D726563657074696F6E','<h1>May 2012: Graduate Reception</h1>\r\n<h2>Class of 2012</h2>\r\n<p>Howdy! Welcome to the Colleges of Geosciences Graduation Reception honoring the Class of 2012.</p>\r\n<p>Today it is time to join our graduates in celebrating this important landmark in life with other students, parents, friends and relatives. On behalf of the faculty and staff in the College of Geosciences, I can say it is our great pleasure to join with you in this celebration. Tomorrow, will be the time to participate in the larger ceremony at Reed Arena.</p>\r\n<p>We say that \"It\'s time for Texas A&amp;M\" for many reasons. We say it because as a top 20 national research university, Texas A&amp;M constantly produces findings that improve lives and advance knowledge across the globe. We say it because we know that those activities also lead to outstanding high-impact educational opportunities for our students, such as hands-on research experiences, internships, and study abroad, that transforms their thinking and prepares them to be leaders and innovators in their careers. And we say \"it\'s time for Texas A&amp;M\" because our graduates have never been more recognized or more successful at putting their education to work for the benefit of society.</p>\r\n<p>Today, I hope that you graduates take away two other perspectives on time: first that It\'s time for Geosciences and second that the perspective on time that and education Geosciences yields, confers on you a special responsibility to lead with a unique perspective in mind whether in the work place or in the community.</p>\r\n<p>Today you graduate with degrees in Geosciences at a time when our field has never been more important to society. Earth, energy, and the environment are on everyone\'s minds. The questions are many. How will we live sustainably and maintain a high standard of living? How will we ensure a sustainable energy future? How can we ensure our resilience for bouncing back from disaster – natural or man made? How will we adapt to climate change? It is you graduates that we will be relying on to answer these questions.</p>\r\n<p>And it is in that reliance that the second perspective on time that I mentioned comes in. Geoscientists understand about geologic time. That time creeps along in increments of hundreds, or thousands, or millions, or billions of years. In that amount of time, often orders of magnitude longer than the human life span, you learn that a lot can and will change. Mountains form and erode, rivers change their course, civilizations come and go. You see how climates and people and landforms adapt to change over long spans of time.</p>\r\n<p>At the other end of the spectrum, you understand that time in the geosciences can be instantaneous: the violent ground shaking from an earthquake, an erupting volcano, the sweeping wall of water from a tsunami, the explosion of an oil rig, the breeching of a river levee, a passing tornado or hurricane. These are events that happen in an instant and can affect lives in the millions.</p>\r\n<p>What is so unique about this understanding? I ask you: how many people do you know or see on TV who think almost entirely within the instantaneous time frame? What\'s for lunch? My gas gauge light has been on for two days.</p>\r\n<p>What Geography exam? It\'s in an hour?!?</p>\r\n<p>Among many skills and talents you take with you from Texas A&amp;M, you take with you the capability to see the long term and the short term together. You understand for example, that development of the huge gas reserves in Eagleford shale in South Texas that formed ca. 100 Ma, is essential to a clean, sustainable, energy-independent future for our country in the next 10s of years. But you also are able to understand that there can be long-term consequences to this rapid development to our communities in the form of risks to water supply and air pollution, and that shorter term actions may be necessary to avert those risks.</p>\r\n<p>Some of you may be working on extracting gas from the Eagleford when you leave here. Others may be working to make sure that our air and water supply is clean. Those of you who choose a career outside geosciences, may still contribute expertise to the community where you live by being able to weigh in on decisions related to drought or flood preparedness.</p>\r\n<p>Among Texas A&amp;M\'s core values are commitments to leadership and selfless-service. Tomorrow, you will begin to take your place as leaders in the work place, in your community, and in the Geosciences. In doing so, I ask that you put that long-term perspective to work in the short term. We are counting on you.</p>\r\n<p>And now it is time to begin the real celebration. After all, there are probably a lot of you thinking that after all the classes, and research and thesis writing, it\'s really just time to get a life!</p>\r\n<p>Before I ask the Class of 2011 to stand and be recognized, I first want to acknowledge some other very important people.</p>\r\n<p>Let me begin by asking those faculty members who are present to please stand and be recognized. It is they that have worked tirelessly to prepare you for the future by challenging you to perform at your best, and still be there to support you when you thought the challenge was insurmountable. I\'m sure you appreciate their efforts even more than I do.</p>\r\n<p>Supporting the faculty and the college, are many staff members, including advisors who have helped you navigate the system here at Texas A&amp;M. Would those staff members who are present, please stand and accept our thanks for your outstanding work.</p>\r\n<p>Wherever there are successful graduates, there are parents, family, and close friends who have faithfully sacrificed and supported them as they pursued their goal. Would all parents, family, and friends of graduates who are here please stand and be recognized. They couldn\'t have done it without you. We could not have done it without you. Thank you.</p>\r\n<p>CONCLUSION</p>\r\n<p>We know great things will come from all the graduates. Please keep in touch. Send email and check out the web site. We like to brag about the success of our former students.</p>\r\n<p>Again, congratulations class of 2011! We will see you tomorrow at 9 am at Reed Arena.</p>','',-2,50,'2013-07-12 15:48:43',8,'','2013-07-12 16:02:53',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 15:48:43','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',1,4,'','',1,1,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(123,318,'June 1, 2012: GeoX',X'6A756E652D312D323031322D67656F78','<h1>June 1, 2012: GeoX Welcome</h1>\r\n<p>Howdy!</p>\r\n<p>It is my great pleasure to welcome the second GeoX class. I am so pleased you are here, and I am confident when you leave next week, your lives will be changed.</p>\r\n<p>Why do I say that? I can personally relate to you that exposure to geosciences when I was not much older than you changed my life. I am a seismologist—I like to blow things up. I have worked in the oil fields and in the classroom. And now I am proud to be dean of the best college of its kind in the United States.</p>\r\n<p>You should also know that 75% of last year\'s GeoX class are entering Texas A&amp;M this year as freshman geosciences majors. Last summer indeed changed their life. You will hear today why geosciences is so important. But you will know it in your bones, I am confident, by the end of this week.</p>\r\n<p>This week you will also experience life as an Aggie.</p>\r\n<p>Around here, we say that \"It\'s time for Texas A&amp;M\" for many reasons. We say it because Texas A&amp;M constantly produces findings that improve lives and advance knowledge across the globe. We say it because we know that those activities lead to outstanding educational opportunities such as hands-on research experiences, internships, and study abroad. And we say \"it\'s time for Texas A&amp;M\" because our graduates continue to be recognized for their success at using their education for the benefit of society.</p>\r\n<p>Yes, it is time for Texas A&amp;M, but also It\'s time for Geosciences. Today Geosciences has never been more important. The questions are many. How do we sustain our planet and maintain a high standard of living? How do secure our energy future? How do we bounce back from disaster – natural or manmade? How will we adapt to climate change? Students who graduate with degrees in geosciences will be at the forefront in answering these questions.</p>\r\n<p>Think back over the last few weeks. What were the headlines you remember?</p>\r\n<p>Two destructive—and unusual—earthquakes just occurred in Italy.</p>\r\n<p>Geoscientists correlate recent U.S. earthquakes with drilling in gas shales.</p>\r\n<p>Debris from last year\'s tsunami is washing ashore in Alaska.</p>\r\n<p>And fracking itself—a revolutionary drilling technology—raises concerns about water-table depletion and pollution.</p>\r\n<p>The 2011 drought cost Texas and the Southwest billions of dollars. And worldwide, monitoring from space shows enormous groundwater depletion, which has enormous effects on food and water supplies.</p>\r\n<p>We have had destructive tornadoes in the Dallas area, and who can forget the wildfires that destroyed entire communities and neighborhoods last summer and fall?</p>\r\n<p>But whatever the headline, we have in the College of Geosciences working on each of these challenges. Our State Climatologist is called upon daily to comment on drought and climate conditions. Another of our researchers is responsible for the camera system on the new, enhanced, and bigger Rover due to land on Mars in August, after being launched in November. Another scientist has just returned from an international scientific expedition that drilled directly into the accretionary wedge, a formation whose movement set of the earthquake and subsequent tsunami off the coast of Japan.</p>\r\n<p>These are only three examples of the caliber of people who you will study with in the College of Geosciences.</p>\r\n<p>If any of these topics pique your interest, then it is time for you to be in the geosciences because our professors . . . and our students . . . are working on every single one of those topics and dozens more.</p>\r\n<p>Turn to the business pages online or in print, and what are your top stories—the price of oil . . . and gold . . . and copper and silver. What are the largest companies in the world? Eight of the top 10 in the world are oil and gas. All geosciences.</p>\r\n<p>If I still haven\'t convinced you, consider this. Our students have recently been or will be in a Costa Rican cloud forest, in the mountains of Italy and a fishing village in Belize. They are on ships as close as the Gulf and as far as the Antarctic, in New Zealand fjords and in colonias along the Texas-Mexican border. They have set off dynamite charges in Wyoming—I know, I was there to conduct the study—measured rip currents off the Florida coast and collected evidence of a growing Dead Zone in the Gulf of Mexico.</p>\r\n<p>Still not convinced that it\'s your time for geosciences? According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, four of the top 10 jobs in science, the fastest growing jobs between now and 2016, will go to geoscientists:</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 30px;\">No. 1: environmental scientists<br />No. 2: hydrologists<br />No. 3: geoscientists<br />and No. 6: atmospheric scientists</p>\r\n<p>There is a growing—more like a galloping—need for geoscientists. These days, median salaries range from $60,000 to over $100,000. Professions such as petroleum geologists earn even more. According to the American Association of Petroleum Geologists, the starting salary for graduates with zero to 2 years experience and a B.S. degree start at $72,000 and go to nearly $110,000 for a Ph.D.</p>\r\n<p>Yes, it is time for geosciences.</p>\r\n<p>So, enjoy your week here. Learn. Make friends. Explore. See, taste, feel, hear, smell the world of geosciences. Welcome to Aggieland. And welcome to Geosciences. And I want to see all of you in a year or two at Freshman Convocation.</p>','',-2,50,'2013-07-12 15:50:14',8,'','2013-07-12 16:02:53',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 15:50:14','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',1,3,'','',1,1,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(124,319,'November 3, 2012: Broadcast Meteorology Workshop',X'6E6F76656D6265722D332D323031322D62726F6164636173742D6D6574656F726F6C6F67792D776F726B73686F70','<h1>November 3, 2012: Broadcast Meteorology Workshop</h1>\r\n<p>Nov. 3, 2012</p>\r\n<p>Howdy!</p>\r\n<p>I am pleased to welcome you on behalf of the College of Geosciences to our first broadcast&nbsp;meteorology workshop. I hope you will find time today to talk to some of our folks in&nbsp;Geosciences about the college, and if you have any questions, stop me or any of my&nbsp;colleagues, and we will be glad to answer them.</p>\r\n<p>I know some of you are graduates of this program, and to you, I say \"Welcome back. Come see us more often.\" For those who may not be familiar with Atmospheric Sciences at Texas A&amp;M, I can say without qualification that this is an outstanding department by any measure. You are in good hands today.</p>\r\n<p>I know that I personally have a lot to learn today. I do know that your profession is more important than ever. Our increasingly complex world demands constant communication, from Tweets to chat, from Weather.com to National Weather Service advisories, the public depends on you to provide accurate and timely information, 24 hours a day. Hurricane Sandy is just the most recent example of how vital your roles are in everyone\'s lives. I doubt very few people in the country today were not glued to the Weather Channel or other network outlet to keep updated on the forecast of the storm\'s path. What you do on a daily basis affects human lives, impacts the national and global economy and influences policy decisions about the environment. It is a vital role, and one that demands constant communication.</p>\r\n<p>I was pleased to learn that the theme of today\'s meeting is communications: better communications between the professionals and the college, between broadcast meteorologists and the National Weather Service employees, and between all meteorologists and the public.<br />The College of Geosciences has also embraced communications—our theme is Commit to Communicate—to enhance the quality of the educational program for our students. Our goal is to provide students with increased opportunities to think, write and speak about the subject matter and skills they are acquiring. I am sure all of you in this room can appreciate how important this mandate is for our students. Through this initiative, students receive targeted instruction and detailed feedback across a range of courses and learning experiences. Through writing and speaking, students gain clarity of thought and the ability to reflect on their intellectual and personal growth. We join then in making a personal and sustained commitment to our shared vision of lifelong learning through enhanced communication.</p>\r\n<p>The College of Geosciences\' emphasis on effective communication aligns our educational goals with your requirements for clear communications We are committed to graduating the students who can contribute the most effectively in this complex world, who can communicate the science accurately, and who have the personal insight and awareness to be good stewards of our planet.<br />As we learn together today, I challenge you to think how we can all improve communications between ourselves and to the public at large.</p>\r\n<p>Enjoy the day, and please let me know your thoughts on how our students can best meet the communications challenges for now and in the future.</p>','',-2,50,'2013-07-12 15:51:20',8,'','2013-07-12 16:02:53',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 15:51:20','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',1,2,'','',1,3,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(125,320,'March 3, 2012: Scholarship Banquet',X'6D617263682D332D323031322D7363686F6C6172736869702D62616E71756574','<h1>March 3, 2012: Scholarship Banquet</h1>\r\n<p>Howdy!</p>\r\n<p>Diane has just introduced you to all the donors, and now it is my pleasure to acknowledge the College of Geosciences scholarship recipients. Will all students who have received a scholarship or fellowship please stand.</p>\r\n<p>Thank all of you for being here tonight—supporters and scholars. As dean of the college of Geosciences, this is one of my favorite events, the opportunity to thank the people who have made a college education possible for many of our students.</p>\r\n<p>By training, I am a geophysicist. As a dean, I am an administrator. But first and foremost I am an educator. Along with the faculty you see here in this room, I have willingly dedicated my life to preparing new generations of geoscientists. Together we can provide the knowledge, we can mentor, and even counsel and coach. . . but it takes people like you, our supporters, to make it possible for so many of these students to be here in the first place. So, again, thank you. [Lead in applause? Diane has already acknowledged them.]<br />This evening, I want to tell you a little about how we have refocused our College\'s direction. And why it is critical that these students today have the skills and background for tomorrow.</p>\r\n<p>We recently reshaped our College\'s vision: The College of Geosciences will lead in establishing the geosciences as the most important and impactful scientific discipline in the 21st century.</p>\r\n<p>Let me repeat. This college . . . at Texas A&amp;M . . . will lead the geosciences as the most important discipline in the 21st century.<br />Why is geosciences if the defining field of the 21st century?</p>\r\n<p>We hear about the marvels of modern-day medicine, or the newest breakthrough in technology. But what do these things matter if we cannot breath, drink fresh water, or transport ourselves and our products in a cost-effective way?</p>\r\n<p>Consider this.</p>\r\n<p>Worldwide, the number of deaths due to hurricanes averages 63,000 lives a year. But no one wears colored ribbons for hurricane relief.</p>\r\n<p>Three-and-half million people die from water-related diseases a year. Yes, medical science addresses the disease, but it is geoscientists who address the problems of access, quantity and quality.</p>\r\n<p>Let\'s talk about energy. We are producing more oil in the United States than ever—5 million barrels a day. But Russia is producing 10 million. Many of you in this room know better than anyone else that the energy industry—traditional and alternative—is the single most force that drives the global economy and shapes the geopolitical landscape.</p>\r\n<p>Even closer to home, the Texas drought has cost the state more than $5 billion dollars this past year alone (confirm with N-G). We have researchers working day and night to find ways to better predict drought cycles, identify factors other than lack of rainfall, and advise the public how to prepare for these events.</p>\r\n<p>Who is best positioned to meet these daily challenges that confront every human being on this planet?</p>\r\n<p>We are.</p>\r\n<p>It is the geographers, the geologists, the geophysicists, the oceanographers, and the atmospheric and environmental scientists who have the experience and the expertise to engage other disciplines in meeting the challenges of the Twenty-First century.</p>\r\n<p>The sustainability of human society depends more on the geosciences than on any other discipline.</p>\r\n<p>Yet, historically we\'ve failed to make our case. We are often invisible to government, funding agencies, foundations, industry and, yes, even our next-door neighbors. Therefore, through the students sitting next to you, you are critical in helping us make the case for our future.</p>\r\n<p>The next steps have to be these.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>We have to lead—we the College of Geosciences--in producing graduates of diverse backgrounds who become leaders in industry, government agencies, and educational institutions.</li>\r\n<li>We have to lead research that is interdisciplinary, innovative, and widely translated and communicated. and</li>\r\n<li>We have to prepare all students to develop informed, life-long views on how to translate scientific knowledge into policy decisions that benefit a global society.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>So, we ask that you continue to be a partner with us to achieve these goals.</p>\r\n<p>I will give you one example of how your support over time makes a difference. Tonight we recognize Murry Page as our guest of honor. You may be surprised to learn that Mr. Page is the College\'s single largest donor. Among his contributions, he has given more than 500 thousand dollars in scholarships over the past 15 years. This support has provided more than 120 scholarships, allowing students to come to Texas A&amp;M and study in the College of Geosciences when financially, they might not have had this opportunity otherwise. Murry has given his support quietly and without fanfare. Let me tell you why Murry contributes with such generosity of spirit. Murry is from the Class of 1951—a vintage year for our college . Dudley Hughes and Dan Hughes and George Crocker, are also from this class.</p>\r\n<p>Murry\'s older sister gave up an opportunity to attend SMU so she could help support their family. Emma Lynn Page Case—11 years Murry\'s senior—made it her mission to ensure that he receive a college education, even when it meant she could not. And so Murry came to Texas A&amp;M to study geology. After working for a mud logging company, he was hired by the newly established Coastal Corporation in 1955, and he stayed with the company until he retired in 1990. He went about his career much like he supports our students: quietly, competently and with great impact. Oscar Wyatt, Coastal\'s founder, came to rely on Murry Page so much that when Murry said drill, Wyatt did. Without question, Murry\'s recommendation was heavily relied upon.</p>\r\n<p>From this small start-up, Coastal became a multi-billion dollar company by the time Murry retired as its executive vice president for exploration.</p>\r\n<p>Murry has given the same kind of support to the College of Geosciences as he did to Coastal: goal-oriented, visionary, and focused. His 15 year trust has provided -one million-dollars to our college, and Murry has now arranged to bridge this support so that scholarships will continue to come to the college throughout his lifetime, and additionally he has provided for these to then continue in perpetuity. We asked him to reflect on why he gives back to Texas A&amp;M. Again, Murry\'s answer is simple and direct. \"I always promised myself,\" he says, \"that if ever I were in a position to help others to have the same opportunity my sister provided for me, I would do whatever I could.\"</p>\r\n<p>I know each of you in this room also has a resonant story of why you give back to Texas A&amp;M. And I know all the scholarship recipients have an equally compelling story of what your support means to them. But we would all do well to follow Murry\'s personal and professional examples. As a college, as a faculty and as students, we all must be goal-oriented, visionary and focused.<br />Your support, and Murry\'s, is the bridge that helps us meet our goals of providing an educated, dedicated and diverse geosciences workforce. In summary, I thank you on behalf of the College for the tremendous contributions—not just in monetary terms but in being with us in achieving our vision to be the leaders of the most important and impactful discipline of the 21st century.</p>\r\n<p>Enjoy the rest of your evening and students, be sure to find and thank our generous donors.</p>','',-2,50,'2013-07-12 15:53:38',8,'','2013-07-12 16:02:53',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 15:53:38','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',1,1,'','',1,7,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(126,321,'April 22, 2010: CACE Conference',X'617072696C2D32322D323031302D636163652D636F6E666572656E6365','<h1>April 22, 2010: CACE Conference</h1>\r\n<p>Texas A&amp;M University,<br />Thursday, April 22, 2010<br />Annenberg Presidential Center</p>\r\n<p>Howdy. It is my great pleasure to be able to address such an audience, a group who is tackling the critical issues of air quality and the environment. I can think of few issues that are as vital to the health, well-being and security of the state and nation, and I am proud that the College of Geosciences is able to contribute to such an undertaking.</p>\r\n<p>I would first like to acknowledge, and thank, Renyi Zhang for his leadership, not only of the Center for Air Chemistry and the Environment, but for the outstanding job he does in all that he undertakes, in his research, his teaching and his service. The College and the University are better places because of dedicated scientists and educators like Renyi.</p>\r\n<p>Next, I would like to tell you a little about the College of Geosciences—and if I may, a little bit about myself. I arrived here in August after spending 18 years at the University at Texas at El Paso where I was a professor of geology and geophysics and associate dean in the College of Science. I am a seismologist and petroleum geoscientist by training, but the unique entity that is the Texas A&amp;M College of Geosciences intrigued me. If I could describe our college in one word, it would be \"interdisciplinary.\" I am sure most of you in this room, at a conference dedicated to reaching across the disciplines to address a societal problem, to look at from all angles in a desire to reach a comprehensive solution, will appreciate what we do in Geosciences.</p>\r\n<p>Our blend of disciplines complements one another and offers outstanding opportunities for collaboration. Just as the Center for Atmospheric Chemistry and the Environment does, and just as you in this room have done today.</p>\r\n<p>We our home to one of the most comprehensive concentrations of geosciences students, faculty and research scientists in the country. Our departments of Atmospheric Sciences, Geography, Geology, Geophysics, Oceanography, Environmental Geosciences and Water Management educate the scientists, educators, technicians, policymakers, and industry leaders who will shape the future of our planet.  INSERT INTO `jos_content` (`id`, `asset_id`, `title`, `alias`, `introtext`, `fulltext`, `state`, `catid`, `created`, `created_by`, `created_by_alias`, `modified`, `modified_by`, `checked_out`, `checked_out_time`, `publish_up`, `publish_down`, `images`, `urls`, `attribs`, `version`, `ordering`, `metakey`, `metadesc`, `access`, `hits`, `metadata`, `featured`, `language`, `xreference`)
