By combining the scientific exploration of Earth with its human dimensions, we are developing a new understanding of the dynamics that have shaped Earth\'s past, present and future. Our five research centers – the Geochemical and Environmental Research Group, the Integrated Ocean Drilling Program, Texas Sea Grant, the Center for Tectonophysics, Berg-Hughes Center for Petroleum and Sedimentary Systems and, of course, the Center for Atmospheric Chemistry and the Environment are essential elements of this scientific exploration and outreach. Interdiscipline cooperation truly defines in our college, and we are delighted to share our faculty, expertise and service with this approach.</p>\r\n<p>I will not bore you with a lot of statistics, but I have some that may interest you. For the first time, we expect our enrollment to top 1,000 students next fall, and our goal of attaining a more diverse student body is increasing each semester. Our Environmental Sciences department is experiencing a boom, and our interdisciplinary program in Water Management is assuming an increasingly important role in our mission of education, research and service. The department of Atmospheric Sciences and Meteorology is unique in the state. I am sure after hearing many of the speakers at this conference from Atmo, as we affectionately call it, you can appreciate the abundance of talent and dedication we offer.</p>\r\n<p>Although we are the smallest college—in size—on campus, we have, at about $102 million dollars, the largest expenditure of research dollars. And our research endeavors, like this conference, strive to address the issues that shape the world around us.</p>\r\n<p>The future of the college, especially centers such as CACE that contribute to the betterment of society, has never looked brighter. I would like to share with you our current and future research priorities. We will be investing more time, money and talent in programs that address water resources, geohazards, environmental studies and geochemistry, climate research, crust and mantle dynamics, coastal processes, earth observation, remote sensing, and geospatial studies. Specific areas that target these priorities are:</p>\r\n<p>The Integrated Ocean Drilling Program, an international effort, sails the world over to investigate among other unifying topics such as paleoclimate and climate changes through time.</p>\r\n<p>Climate studies, an issue that involves all of our departments and many of our centers, will concentrate in modeling prediction, societal impacts and Arctic, coastal and carbon- sequestration research.</p>\r\n<p>We plan to be pioneer new programs in the geospatial sciences including earth observation that will monitor among other things air quality throughout the world (??? This probably needs to be vetted by someone more expert than I.)<br />And last, we believe that water management and related issues emerge as a dominant concern for the planet. We plan to be at the forefront in training those who make the critical decisions that perform the research, set the policy and develop the measures to protect this vital resource.</p>\r\n<p>In closing, I want to assure all of you that the College stands, not only behind your hard work in addressing environmental and air quality issues, but also in helping you lead in this endeavor. Thank you for letting us play a key role in bringing such diverse perspectives together in the service to the state and nation.</p>','',-2,50,'2013-07-12 15:59:50',8,'','2013-07-12 16:02:53',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 15:59:50','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":