	(127,322,'February 19, 2010: Science is a Blast',X'66656272756172792D31392D323031302D736369656E63652D69732D612D626C617374','<h1>February 19, 2010: Science is a Blast</h1>\r\n<p>WISE Conference<br />Texas A&amp;M, February 19, 2010</p>\r\n<p>Thank you, Shari, for that kind introduction. Howdy. I am honored to be here, and I want to thank the organizers for inviting me and for the compliment that I might be able to give career advice and life insight to women who, just by being here in the first place, suggests that you are already successful in science and engineering.</p>\r\n<p>Science has given me a rewarding and fulfilling career and life that, in my case, has both literally and metaphorically been a blast. As a seismologist, who explores the origin of the Earth\'s lithosphere, the land we live on, by setting off large explosives blasts to create seismic waves, I can honestly say that my life has also been a blast. Today I will use the letters in BLAST as acronym for the key elements that have guided me and, without which, I would not be standing here. Those five elements are Balance, Listening, Alliances, Self-confidence and Tenacity.</p>\r\n<p>As neat as it would be to keep these five letters in \"blast\" order, I am going to skip around, and begin with the second letter, L, because the first element I came to understand was to listen, and to follow my inner voice. I grew up in a nonscientific family. No one in my family passed algebra. Ever. But out the front door of my Philadelphia row house were the Franklin Institute, the Museum of Natural Sciences, and the Public Library. And my childhood was largely spent exploring their nooks and crannies. When not pressing my nose against the diorama windows, I built model rockets, gazed at the stars in the planetarium, and constructed butterfly nets. My childhood interests were astronomy, and ecology. Geology was not my first bent. When they first brought a moon rock to Philadelphia, there under the great statue of Benjamin Franklin, I thought that is pretty boring tiny little white rock.</p>\r\n<p>By the time I got to Princeton, I knew I would go into science, but I had not yet learned to trust my inner voice. As a prospective biology major, I took the mandatory freshman courses in biology and chemistry. But I hated the way the pre-med competition of these classes especially because I was not interested in medicine. For a time, I thought of becoming a history or philosophy major.</p>\r\n<p>At a low point in the spring of my freshman year, I found my interests in ecology and eco systems kept calling me, and somehow it occurred to me go see an undergraduate advisor in the geology department. That geology professor immediately made me feel welcome to the discipline and introduced me to peers and other professors who shared a vision for the geosciences that I had only just gotten a glimpse at. That taught me about another essential element for success, the importance of alliances. Not only do you need to form alliances with mentors but also with peers, with colleagues and with friends and family. The romantic vision of the solitary scientist blazing a lone intellectual path is no way to do science in my mind. Collaboration is the key. New discoveries come from interacting within others in a vibrant intellectual atmosphere. This is a highlight I see for scientists and engineers in training today. Research has become more interdisciplinary, and the willingness to share information in a collaborative effort to create results such that the sum greater are than the parts is much more common now.</p>\r\n<p>Furthermore, I think collaboration just makes research more fun.</p>\r\n<p>By the time I graduated from college, I had begun to pay more attention to my inner voice, which told me that I was not yet ready for graduate school. So I ended up in the oil patch, based in New Orleans, and that is when I began to appreciate a third key element: balance. Here I was, a kid from the East Coast, thrust into the Deep South for the first time in my life. I learned there the importance of family and friends, through the cultural traditions engrained in the New Orleans lifestyle. I joined a local soccer team and formed friendships both in the office and in the community. I began to learn balance, the importance of having fun and seeking people outside my own sphere. Later, when I was at the University of Texas at El Paso, I joined a tennis team, and I balanced family and career, learning every day from own child. Raising children teaches you about life. As a scientist, I had to learn that childrearing is not a rational process. It is not black and white, and with children you are always living in the gray zone. There is much to be learned from that.</p>\r\n<p>And from balance come inspiration and intuition, elements crucial to the scientific process. Intuition doesn\'t come until you set your rational mind aside, when that \"aha\" moment comes in the shower, on the tennis court or in the kitchen cooking enchiladas. It can come in your sleep, as it did to James Watson when he dreamt of spiral staircases that transformed into the double helix. Rene Descartes arrived at the basics of the scientific method through a series of dreams, and the formula for benzene came from a dream about a snake seizing his tail. The point is that none of these scientific breakthroughs came about in the lab or from formulas on a blackboard. It\'s probably more productive to keep a notebook on your bedside table or in you gym bag.</p>\r\n<p>These experiences bring me to the fourth important element, self-confidence. Going into the oil industry right out of college was exactly the right thing for me to do. I learned that I could perform and thrive in a practical setting, to create new knowledge, to find oil. I learned that my contributions to a project were important and that I could work collaboratively as well as solve problems on my own. This belief in my own capabilities had ramifications much later in my career. For example, when I was asked to be department chair the day I received tenure, I didn\'t hesitate, even though I had never thought of myself as an administrator and leader. Quickly I learned that academic administration is creative and that I thrived on it.</p>\r\n<p>This leads me to a fifth element, which is tenacity, persistence, whatever you want to call it. To me this is the most important of the five. I attribute all of my accomplishments to my tenacity. You can max out on your SAT scores and still flunk out of college. You may know someone who has done just that, or is trying to at this very moment. You can also be an average math and physics student, and still become the company\'s most promising scientist or engineer, even CEO, just by be willing to stick out the process. Most people won\'t. In the early 20th Century, Alfred Wegener, a meteorologist, persisted in defending his unifying and—at that time—heretical theory that the continents were at one time a single, great land mass. Fifty years later, scientists realized he was indeed right and that he should not have been scoffed at.</p>\r\n<p>In my own experience, after serving first as department chair and then as an associate dean at UTEP, I realized that I wanted to move to the next level in the administrative ladder (that inner voice thing again), so I applied for my current job five years ago. When I failed to get it, I concentrated on making sure I would succeed at the next opportunity, either at Texas A&amp;M or at another university of equal rank. I read on leadership, I attended seminars and conferences, I observed other leaders. At the next go-around my persistence paid off.</p>\r\n<p>So, these are the thoughts I want to leave with you</p>\r\n<p><em>Balance</em> your life. Find outside interests and seek people outside your field. Sing, dance, swim, run. Paint, write, read romance novels. Do something outside that lab, so you can be better in the lab.</p>\r\n<p><em>Listen.</em> Listen to the voice inside you, listen to your heart. Then learn to develop your external voice and express your thoughts. You will never let yourself down this way.</p>\r\n<p><em>Form alliances</em> and allegiances, not only with friends and colleagues but with your family, far and wide, nuclear and extended. Scientists and engineers have a reputation for sometimes forgetting the importance of social interaction.</p>\r\n<p>We all need people, we need support and, in return, we need to lend encouragement and guidance.</p>\r\n<p>By listening to your inner voice, you will develop self-confidence. Conquer your fears by doing what your voice says. As scientists and engineers, we often do not trust emotions and are taught that we can resolve any problem by just thinking hard enough. From your emotions come the very instincts that lead to great discoveries and insights, and in order to bring these into the light, you must have the confidence that your inner voice will make things happen for you.</p>\r\n<p>Tenacity. Persistence. Sweat. Whatever you want to call it, this is for me the most important trait. \"I never did anything worth doing by accident,\" Thomas Edison said, \"nor did any of my inventions come by accident. They came by work.\"</p>\r\n<p>Do these things, and you will have a blast in science, in engineering, and in your life.</p>','',-2,50,'2013-07-12 16:00:41',8,'','2013-07-12 16:02:53',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 16:00:41','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',1,13,'','',1,1,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(128,323,'Texas State Climatologist predicts a warm, but normal summer',X'74657861732D73746174652D636C696D61746F6C6F676973742D70726564696374732D612D7761726D2D6275742D6E6F726D616C2D73756D6D6572','<p><img src=\"images/news/summer_s.jpg\" alt=\"summer s\" /></p>\r\n<p>Hot town summer in the city, back of my neck getting dirt and gritty.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p>&nbsp;<img src=\"images/news/summer.png\" alt=\"summer\" width=\"550\" height=\"241\" /></p>\r\n<h1>Texas State Climatologist predicts a warm, but normal summer</h1>\r\n<p>John Nielsen-Gammon, professor of atmospheric sciences at Texas A&amp;M University and the Texas State Climatologist, predicts a somewhat normal summer in terms of rainfall.</p>\r\n<p>\"We\'re starting off fairly promising,\" Nielsen-Gammon said. \"We\'re seeing rain, sometimes even heavy rain, in many parts of the state. It is definitely not as bad as 2011 in terms of rainfall.\"</p>\r\n<p>Forecasts for the next couple of weeks show a continuation in that pattern, but Nielsen-Gammon warns Texans not to read too much into the prediction, as the seasonal forecast still shows a range of possibilities for both above and below average rainfall.</p>\r\n<p>In terms of temperature, it will likely be warmer than normal this summer, as conditions are drier and the ground is likely to heat up more. This will likely bring a hotter summer to the state, he said.</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"wf_caption\" style=\"margin: 10px; float: right; display: inline-block;\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid #000000; margin: auto;\" src=\"images/faculty/ng2012.jpg\" alt=\"ng2012\" width=\"170\" height=\"220\" /><span style=\"clear: both; padding: 3px; width: 164px; display: block;\">John Nielsen-Gammon <br />Regents Professor and State Climatologist <br />979.862.2248 <br />n-g@tamu.edu</span></span>For extreme weather events, tropical forecasts seem to call for an active hurricane season. The Atlantic Ocean is warmer than normal and the El Niño effect is not in place. The odds are rising that one will hit the United States, he said, but no one is yet predicting where landfall will be or if it will occur at all.</p>\r\n<p>\"Despite Ike and Sandy, the United States is overdue for a Category 3 or greater hurricane to make landfall,\" Nielsen-Gammon said.</p>\r\n<p>For more updates on Texas climate, visit the website for the Office of the Texas State Climatologist at <a href=\"http://climatexas.tamu.edu\">climatexas.tamu.edu. </a></p>',-2,11,'2013-07-12 21:17:35',8,'','2013-07-12 22:44:38',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 21:17:35','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',6,2,'','',1,4,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(129,324,'Large Dead Zone Growing In Gulf of Mexico',X'6C617267652D646561642D7A6F6E652D67726F77696E672D696E2D67756C662D6F662D6D657869636F','<p><img src=\"images/news/titration_s.jpg\" alt=\"titration s\" /></p>\r\n<p>The Dead Zone - coming to a Gulf near you.</p>\r\n','\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1>Large Dead Zone Growing In Gulf of Mexico</h1>\r\n<p>Ocean experts had predicted a large “dead zone” area in the Gulf of Mexico this year, and according to the results from a Texas A&amp;M University researcher just back from studying the region, those predictions appear to be right on target.</p>\r\n<p><strong><a style=\"color: #500000; outline-style: none; outline-width: initial; outline-color: initial; text-decoration: none;\" href=\"http://ocean.tamu.edu/profile/SDiMarco\">Steve DiMarco</a></strong>, professor of oceanography and one of the world’s leading experts on the dead zone, says he and a Texas A&amp;M team surveyed areas off the Texas-Louisiana coast last week and found large areas of oxygen-depleted water – an area covering roughly 3,100 square miles, or about the size of Delaware and Rhode Island combined.</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"wf_caption\" style=\"margin: 10px; float: right; display: inline-block;\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid #000000; margin: auto;\" src=\"images/news/dimarco_2013.jpg\" alt=\"dimarco 2013\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /><span style=\"clear: both; padding: 3px; width: 294px; display: block;\">Texas A&amp;M professor Steve DiMarco taking water samples.</span></span>“We found hypoxia (oxygen-depleted water) just about everywhere we looked,” DiMarco reports.</p>\r\n<p>“The most intense area is where you would expect it – off the Louisiana coast south of Atchafalaya Bay and Grande Isle, La.&nbsp; But we also found significant amounts off High Island and near Galveston.&nbsp; The farther south we went, the less we found hypoxia in the water column, but we still found plenty of depleted oxygen waters up to just west of Freeport.</p>\r\n<p>“There is no doubt there is a lot of hypoxia in the Gulf this year.”</p>\r\n<p><strong><a href=\"http://hypoxia.tamu.edu/\">Hypoxia</a></strong> occurs when oxygen levels in seawater drop to dangerously low levels, and persistent hypoxia can potentially result in fish kills and harm marine life, thereby creating a “dead zone” in that particular area.</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"wf_caption\" style=\"margin: 10px; float: right; display: inline-block;\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid #000000; margin: auto;\" src=\"images/news/titration.jpg\" alt=\"titration\" width=\"300\" height=\"340\" /><span style=\"clear: both; padding: 3px; width: 294px; display: block;\">Dissolved oxygen samples for Winkler titration. White indicates hypoxia present.</span></span>Such low levels of oxygen are believed to be caused by nutrient pollution from farm fertilizers as they empty into rivers such as the Mississippi and eventually into the Gulf, or by soil erosion or discharge from sewage treatment plants. The size of the zone has been shown to be influenced by the nutrient runoff, volume of freshwater discharged, and prevailing winds, which controls the freshwater river plume’s movement.</p>\r\n<p>The Mississippi is the largest river in the United States, draining 40 percent of the land area of the country. It also accounts for almost 90 percent of the freshwater runoff into the Gulf of Mexico.</p>\r\n<p>Last year, with much of the Midwest suffering through its worst drought in 100 years, the dead zone measured only 1,580 square miles.</p>\r\n<p>DiMarco’s research on the dead zone is supported by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Association (<strong><a href=\"http://coastalscience.noaa.gov/research/pollution/hypoxia\">NOAA</a></strong>), as part of its long-term commitment to advancing the science to inform management practices aimed at mitigating the hypoxic zone.</p>\r\n<p>“While we await additional data from the entire summer, these early findings start to validate our prediction that we could see one of the largest dead zones ever in the Gulf of Mexico this July,” said Robert Magnien, Ph.D., center director at NOAA’s National Centers for Coastal Ocean Science.</p>\r\n<p>“This is further confirmation of the link between upstream nutrient management decisions and the critical habitats and living resources in the Gulf.”</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"wf_caption\" style=\"margin: 10px; float: right; display: inline-block;\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid #000000; margin: auto;\" src=\"images/faculty/dimarco_2013.jpg\" alt=\"dimarco 2013\" /><span style=\"padding: 3px; display: block;\"><a href=\"http://ocean.tamu.edu/profile/SDimarco\">Steve DiMarco </a><br />Associate Professor <br />979.862.4168 <br />sdimarco@tamu.edu</span></span>DiMarco has made 28 research trips to investigate the dead zone since 2003. His cruise this year carried 10 investigators from Texas A&amp;M and Texas A&amp;M at Galveston and included two research scientists, Matthew Howard and &nbsp;Ruth Perry, five graduate students, Laura Harred, Jordan Young, Yan Zhao, Heather Zimmerle, and Nicole Zuck, and two marine technicians, Eddie Webb and Andrew Dancer (Geochemical and Environmental Research Group). On shore investigators include Lisa Campbell, Wilford Gardner, Shari Yvon-Lewis, and Ethan Grossman , all from Texas A&amp;M, and Antonietta Quigg from Texas A&amp;M-Galveston.</p>\r\n<p>DiMarco says the size of the dead zone off coastal Louisiana has been routinely monitored since 1985. Previous research has also shown that nitrogen levels in the Gulf related to human activities have tripled over the past 50 years.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1em;\"><strong>###</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1em;\">Media contact: <a href=\"mailto:keith-randall@tamu.edu\">Keith Randall,</a> News &amp; Information Services, at (979) 845-4644 or <a href=\"mailto:sdimarco@tamu.edu\">Steve DiMarco</a> at (979) 862-4168</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><em>June 27, 2013</em></span></p>',-2,11,'2013-07-12 21:27:53',8,'','2013-07-12 22:42:10',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 21:27:53','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',6,1,'','',1,9,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*',''),
	(130,325,'Lightning Prone Houston Now Has World’s Best Detection System',X'6C696768746E696E672D70726F6E652D686F7573746F6E2D6E6F772D6861732D776F726C642D732D626573742D646574656374696F6E2D73797374656D','<p><img src=\"images/news/lightning_s.jpg\" alt=\"lightning s\" /></p>\r\n<p>The country\'s best system just got better, thanks to Richard Orville.</p>\r\n','\r\n<h1>Lightning Prone Houston Now Has World’s Best Detection System</h1>\r\n<p>The country\'s best system to detect lightning strikes – located in and around the Houston area – just got better, thanks to a complete overhaul and new software by its designer and one of the world\'s leading lightning experts, Texas A&amp;M University atmospheric sciences professor Richard Orville.</p>\r\n<p>The system, known as the Lightning Mapping Array (LMA) system, is the only one of its kind for a large metropolitan area, and the 5 million residents of the greater Houston area reside in an area that is one of the world\'s true hotspots for lightning.</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"wf_caption\" style=\"margin: 10px; float: right; display: inline-block;\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid #000000; margin: auto;\" src=\"images/news/lightning.jpg\" alt=\"lightning\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /><span style=\"clear: both; padding: 3px; width: 294px; display: block;\">Lightning strikes a Houston neighborhood. Photo: Shutterstock</span></span>With thousands of strikes each year, Houston is the lightning center of Texas and one of the world\'s most frequently prone areas for lightning hits. Studies show about 1,800 thunderstorms pound the Earth at any given moment, resulting in about 50 lightning strikes every second.</p>\r\n<p>Orville says Houston averages about 20 strikes per square mile, and receives about 1,700 strikes between June and July alone each year.</p>\r\n<p>\"You need two things for lightning to occur – heat and moisture, and Houston has plenty of both,\" he explains.</p>\r\n<p>The LMA system has 10 sensors placed around the Houston area, plus one in Brazos County and another near Galveston. When a lightning flash occurs, each site notes the precise time (within microseconds) and reports vital data to a central server on the Texas A&amp;M campus. Researchers can then calculate the exact latitude and longitude from where the lightning originated, Orville says.</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"wf_caption\" style=\"margin: 10px; float: right; display: inline-block;\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid #000000; margin: auto;\" src=\"images/news/lightning2.jpg\" alt=\"lightning2\" width=\"270\" height=\"300\" /><span style=\"clear: both; padding: 3px; width: 264px; display: block;\"> Texas A&amp;M graduate students Matt Cullen (left) and Marty Hale helped install lightning sensors around the Houston area. Photo: Texas A&amp;M University</span></span>\"The LMA can give us an advance warning time of from 5 to 20 minutes ahead of time where cloud-to-ground lightning may strike next,\" he adds.</p>\r\n<p>\"When you consider all of the golf courses, public parks, stadiums, lakes and other outdoor sites where people tend to gather, it has the potential to save many lives.\"</p>\r\n<p>The upgraded system now uses solar panels for power, and also includes new Wi-Fi hookups to transmit data for more efficient data transmission, Orville notes.</p>\r\n<p>The $1.2 million system is financed through grants from the National Science Foundation \"and is the best in the world, no doubt about it,\" says Orville, who has studied lightning for more than 30 years.</p>\r\n<p>According to the National Weather Service, about 60 people are killed each year by lightning in the United States. Lightning is the second greatest weather killer. Flood fatalities are No.1.</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"wf_caption\" style=\"margin: 10px; float: right; display: inline-block;\"><img style=\"border: 1px solid #000000; margin: auto;\" src=\"images/faculty/orville.jpg\" alt=\"orville\" /><span style=\"clear: both; padding: 3px; width: 164px; display: block;\"><a href=\"http://atmo.tamu.edu/profile/ROrville\">Richard Orville </a><br />Professor and Director, NOAA/NWS Cooperative Institute for Applied Meteorological Studies <br />979.845.7671 <br />rorville@tamu.edu</span></span>More than 20 years ago, Orville led key studies in the physics of lightning and helped to establish the National Lightning Detection Network. It is located in 48 states and Canada and detects every ground strike of lightning. He has devoted much of his academic career to studying severe storms and the lightning associated with them.</p>\r\n<p>\"The LMA is the best system of its type in the country,\" he confirms.</p>\r\n<p>\"Since it\'s geared toward safety, it will be a great public service device, and it will also give us more knowledge about the nature of lightning.\"</p>\r\n<p>###</p>\r\n<p>About Research at Texas A&amp;M University: As one of the world\'s leading research institutions, Texas A&amp;M is in the vanguard in making significant contributions to the storehouse of knowledge, including that of science and technology. Research conducted at Texas A&amp;M represents an annual investment of more than $700 million. That research creates new knowledge that provides basic, fundamental and applied contributions resulting in many cases in economic benefits to the state, nation and world.</p>\r\n<p>Media contact: <a href=\"mailto:keith-randall@tamu.edu\">Keith Randall,</a> News &amp; Information Services, at (979) 845-4644</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',-2,11,'2013-07-12 21:33:17',8,'','2013-07-12 22:42:44',8,0,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2013-07-12 21:33:17','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\"image_intro\":\"\",\"float_intro\":\"\",\"image_intro_alt\":\"\",\"image_intro_caption\":\"\",\"image_fulltext\":\"\",\"float_fulltext\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_alt\":\"\",\"image_fulltext_caption\":\"\"}','{\"urla\":null,\"urlatext\":\"\",\"targeta\":\"\",\"urlb\":null,\"urlbtext\":\"\",\"targetb\":\"\",\"urlc\":null,\"urlctext\":\"\",\"targetc\":\"\"}','{\"show_title\":\"\",\"link_titles\":\"\",\"show_tags\":\"\",\"show_intro\":\"\",\"info_block_position\":\"\",\"show_category\":\"\",\"link_category\":\"\",\"show_parent_category\":\"\",\"link_parent_category\":\"\",\"show_author\":\"\",\"link_author\":\"\",\"show_create_date\":\"\",\"show_modify_date\":\"\",\"show_publish_date\":\"\",\"show_item_navigation\":\"\",\"show_icons\":\"\",\"show_print_icon\":\"\",\"show_email_icon\":\"\",\"show_vote\":\"\",\"show_hits\":\"\",\"show_noauth\":\"\",\"urls_position\":\"\",\"alternative_readmore\":\"\",\"article_layout\":\"\",\"show_publishing_options\":\"\",\"show_article_options\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_backend\":\"\",\"show_urls_images_frontend\":\"\"}',18,0,'','',1,21,'{\"robots\":\"\",\"author\":\"\",\"rights\":\"\",\"xreference\":\"\",\"tags\":null}',0,'*','');


